=99s
Tim Kaine, shocked Capitol Hill by delivering the Armed Services Committee=
=E2=80=99s most ferocious line of questioning for SecDef nominee Pete Hegse=
th, unleashing a barrage of direct inquiries about allegations of sexual as=
sault, adultery, binge drinking, etcetera. And yet, it was a very different=
 Kaine who showed up earlier today to examine the nomination of his committ=
ee colleague Marco Rubio for secretary of state, calling him
=E2=80=9Cextremely well prepared=E2=80=9D and congratulating him on his nom=
ination. The remarkable split screen highlighted the new style of Dem resis=
tance in Trump 2.0, which still seeks to police norms but is not adversaria=
l for the sake of it.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

But Kaine=E2=80=99s performance also intimated a broader strategic plan for=
 Democrats: to seek coexistence with Trump appointees they can deal with in=
 good faith. =E2=80=9CI think
you=E2=80=99ve seen a hearing with a nominee who=E2=80=94agree or disagree =
with the points he=E2=80=99s made=E2=80=94he=E2=80=99s not talking out of a=
 briefing book,=E2=80=9D Kaine said of Rubio. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve always =
been struck, in working with Senator Rubio on this committee, =E2=80=A6 tha=
t he has a well-developed sense of the world and a passionate interest in a=
ll corners of it.=E2=80=9D Indeed, the Rubio hearing felt like a throwback =
to the pre-George W. Bush era of chumminess, when senators often appeared t=
o be having fun kicking
around issues of import, or even disagreeing on substance, with an intellec=
tual peer.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Somewhere in the middle of the Hegseth-to-Rubio spectrum of collegiality wa=
s Pam Bondi=E2=80=99s hearing for A.G. at Judiciary. Though controversial i=
n her own right=E2=80=94she supported Trump=E2=80=99s efforts to challenge =
Biden=E2=80=99s victory in 2020 and famously
declined ( https://www.nytimes.com/2024/11/22/us/politics/pam-bondi-trump-u=
niversity.html?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281=
%2F15%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2=
F15%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df=
6c60617da42abd12a ) to join the fraud suit against Trump University=E2=80=
=94Bondi is at least qualified on paper for the role she=E2=80=99s seeking.=
 She=E2=80=99s also a polished, former statewide official who is well acqua=
inted with the mores of professional politics=E2=80=94one of which, of cour=
se, is not answering questions. When Democrats repeatedly asked her who won=
 the 2020
presidential election, she repeatedly intoned, =E2=80=9CJoe Biden is the pr=
esident of the United States.=E2=80=9D Likewise, she gave lawyerly answers =
when pressed about the January 6 insurrection and whether she had the will =
to push back against any questionable commands from Trump.

All that to say, she didn=E2=80=99t win much Democratic enthusiasm during h=
er five-hour-plus appearance. But outside of tussling with Mazie Hirono of =
Hawaii, and Alex Padilla and Adam
Schiff of California, most of Bondi=E2=80=99s interactions with Democrats w=
ere collegial in both directions. Expect a much more combative round at the=
 Judiciary Committee when Kash Patel goes before them as the F.B.I. nominee=
 next month.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

And now, here=E2=80=99s Dylan=E2=80=A6

Kingdom Kutler

